TY  - JOUR
T1  - A Typology of Attribution Leadership Research
AU  - McElroy, James C.
Y1  - 1982/07/01
PY  - 1982
DA  - 1982/07/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/amr.1982.4285342
DO  - 10.5465/amr.1982.4285342
T2  - Academy of Management Review
JF  - Academy of Management Review
JO  - AMR
SP  - 413
EP  - 417
VL  - 7
IS  - 3
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - A typology of leadership research utilizing an attributional paradigm is presented. Studies are typed according to three pertinent questions: (1) What is to be studied? (2) Whom do you ask? and (3) What is the purpose of the research? The typology reveals that most of the research using the attribution paradigm is descriptive rather than prescriptive. Moreover, there is a serious lack of prescriptive-process research. Future research matching superior and subordinate attributional tendencies is suggested.
AB  - A typology of leadership research utilizing an attributional paradigm is presented. Studies are typed according to three pertinent questions: (1) What is to be studied? (2) Whom do you ask? and (3) What is the purpose of the research? The typology reveals that most of the research using the attribution paradigm is descriptive rather than prescriptive. Moreover, there is a serious lack of prescriptive-process research. Future research matching superior and subordinate attributional tendencies is suggested.
